# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gcp-cloud-run
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] Autoscaling differs from having a fixed daily, weekly, or yearly cycle of server use in that it is responsive to actual usage patterns, and thus reduces the potential downside of having too few or too many servers for the traffic load.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] For instance, if traffic is usually lower at midnight, then a static scaling solution might schedule some servers to sleep at night, but this might result in downtime on a night where people happen to use the Internet more (for instance, due to a viral news event).
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] Autoscaling, on the other hand, can handle unexpected traffic spikes better.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] In the list below, we use the terminology used by Amazon Web Services (AWS).
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] However, alternative names are noted and terminology that is specific to the names of Amazon services is not used for the names.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] Amazon Web Services launched the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) service in August 2006, that allowed developers to programmatically create and terminate instances (machines).
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] At the time of initial launch, AWS did not offer autoscaling, but the ability to programmatically create and terminate instances gave developers the flexibility to write their own code for autoscaling.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] Third-party autoscaling software for AWS began appearing around April 2008.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] These included tools by Scalr and RightScale.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] RightScale was used by Animoto, which was able to handle Facebook traffic by adopting autoscaling.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] On May 18, 2009, Amazon launched its own autoscaling feature along with Elastic Load Balancing, as part of Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] Autoscaling is now an integral component of Amazon's EC2 offering.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] Autoscaling on Amazon Web Services is done through a web browser or the command line tool.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] In May 2016 Autoscaling was also offered in AWS ECS Service.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] On-demand video provider Netflix documented their use of autoscaling with Amazon Web Services to meet their highly variable consumer needs.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] They found that aggressive scaling up and delayed and cautious scaling down served their goals of uptime and responsiveness best.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] In an article for *TechCrunch*, Zev Laderman, the co-founder and CEO of Newvem, a service that helps optimize AWS cloud infrastructure, recommended that startups use autoscaling in order to keep their Amazon Web Services costs low.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] Various best practice guides for AWS use suggest using its autoscaling feature even in cases where the load is not variable.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] Netflix's internal best practices require every instance to be in an autoscaling group, and its conformity monkey terminates any instance not in an autoscaling group in order to enforce this best practice.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] On June 27, 2013, Microsoft announced that it was adding autoscaling support to its Windows Azure cloud computing platform.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] Documentation for the feature is available on the Microsoft Developer Network.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] Oracle Cloud Platform allows server instances to automatically scale a cluster in or out by defining an auto-scaling rule.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] These rules are based on CPU and/or memory utilization and determine when to add or remove nodes.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] On November 17, 2014, the Google Compute Engine announced a public beta of its autoscaling feature for use in Google Cloud Platform applications.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] As of March 2015, the autoscaling tool is still in Beta.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] In a blog post in August 2014, a Facebook engineer disclosed that the company had started using autoscaling to bring down its energy costs.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] The blog post reported a 27% decline in energy use for low traffic hours (around midnight) and a 10-15% decline in energy use over the typical 24-hour cycle.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] Autoscaling by default uses *reactive* decision approach for dealing with traffic scaling: scaling only happens in response to real-time changes in metrics.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] In some cases, particularly when the changes occur very quickly, this reactive approach to scaling is insufficient.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] Two other kinds of autoscaling decision approaches are described below.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] This is an approach to autoscaling where changes are made to the minimum size, maximum size, or desired capacity of the autoscaling group at specific times of day.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] Scheduled scaling is useful, for instance, if there is a known traffic load increase or decrease at specific times of the day, but the change is too sudden for reactive approach based autoscaling to respond fast enough.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] AWS autoscaling groups support scheduled scaling.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] This approach to autoscaling uses predictive analytics.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] The idea is to combine recent usage trends with historical usage data as well as other kinds of data to predict usage in the future, and autoscale based on these predictions.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] For parts of their infrastructure and specific workloads, Netflix found that Scryer, their predictive analytics engine, gave better results than Amazon's reactive autoscaling approach.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/autoscaling] On November 20, 2018, AWS announced that predictive scaling would be available as part of its autoscaling offering.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/cloud-native-computing-foundation] The **Cloud Native Computing Foundation** (**CNCF**) is a subsidiary of the Linux Foundation founded in 2015 to support cloud-native computing.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/cloud-native-computing-foundation] It was announced alongside Kubernetes 1.0, an open source container cluster manager, which was contributed to the Linux Foundation by Google as a seed technology.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/cloud-native-computing-foundation] Founding members include Google, CoreOS, Mesosphere, Red Hat, Twitter, Huawei, Intel, RX-M, Cisco, IBM, Docker, Univa, and VMware.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/cloud-native-computing-foundation] Today, CNCF is supported by over 450 members.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/cloud-native-computing-foundation] In August 2018 Google announced that it was handing over operational control of Kubernetes to the community.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/function-as-a-service] Function as a Service is a subset of the serverless computing ecosystem.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/function-as-a-service] The "Grain of Sand Anti-pattern" refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/function-as-a-service] "Lambda Pinball" is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure Functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/function-as-a-service] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/function-as-a-service] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/function-as-a-service] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/function-as-a-service] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/function-as-a-service] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/function-as-a-service] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/function-as-a-service] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/function-as-a-service] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/function-as-a-service] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/function-as-a-service] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/function-as-a-service] Function as a service workloads may encounter migration obstacles due to service lock-in from tight vendor integrations.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/function-as-a-service] Hexagonal architecture can facilitate workload portability.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] On Unix-like operating systems, this feature can be seen as an advanced implementation of the standard chroot mechanism, which changes the apparent root folder for the current running process and its children.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] In addition to isolation mechanisms, the kernel often provides resource-management features to limit the impact of one container's activities on other containers.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] Linux containers are all based on the virtualization, isolation, and resource management mechanisms provided by the Linux kernel, notably Linux namespaces and cgroups.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] Although the word *container* most commonly refers to OS-level virtualization, it is sometimes used to refer to fuller virtual machines operating in varying degrees of concert with the host OS, such as Microsoft's Hyper-V containers.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] For an overview of virtualization since 1960, see Timeline of virtualization technologies.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] On ordinary operating systems for personal computers, a computer program can see (even though it might not be able to access) all the system's resources.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may allow or deny access to such resources based on which program requests them and the user account in the context in which it runs.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may also hide those resources, so that when the computer program enumerates them, they do not appear in the enumeration results.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] Nevertheless, from a programming point of view, the computer program has interacted with those resources and the operating system has managed an act of interaction.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] With operating-system-virtualization, or containerization, it is possible to run programs within containers, to which only parts of these resources are allocated.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] A program expecting to see the whole computer, once run inside a container, can only see the allocated resources and believes them to be all that is available.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] Several containers can be created on each operating system, to each of which a subset of the computer's resources is allocated.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] Each container may contain any number of computer programs.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] These programs may run concurrently or separately, and may even interact with one another.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] Containerization has similarities to application virtualization: In the latter, only one computer program is placed in an isolated container and the isolation applies to file system only.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is commonly used in virtual hosting environments, where it is useful for securely allocating finite hardware resources among a large number of mutually-distrusting users.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] System administrators may also use it for consolidating server hardware by moving services on separate hosts into containers on the one server.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization can also be used to run software created for a certain Linux distribution on another distribution, an example is Distrobox.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] Other typical scenarios include separating several programs to separate containers for improved security, hardware independence, and added resource management features.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] The improved security provided by the use of a chroot mechanism, however, is not perfect.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system-level virtualization implementations capable of live migration can also be used for dynamic load balancing of containers between nodes in a cluster.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] This form of virtualization also does not require hardware support for efficient performance.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is not as flexible as other virtualization approaches since it cannot host a guest operating system different from the host one, or a different guest kernel.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] For example, with Linux, different distributions are fine, but other operating systems such as Windows cannot be hosted.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] Operating systems using variable input systematics are subject to limitations within the virtualized architecture.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] Adaptation methods including cloud-server relay analytics maintain the OS-level virtual environment within these applications.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] Solaris partially overcomes the limitation described above with its branded zones feature, which provides the ability to run an environment within a container that emulates an older Solaris 8 or 9 version in a Solaris 10 host.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] However, in 2010 Linux branded zones were removed from Solaris; in 2014 they were reintroduced in Illumos, which is the open source Solaris fork, supporting 32-bit Linux kernels.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] Some implementations provide file-level copy-on-write (CoW) mechanisms.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] (Most commonly, a standard file system is shared between partitions, and those partitions that change the files automatically create their own copies.) This is easier to back up, more space-efficient and simpler to cache than the block-level copy-on-write schemes common on whole-system virtualizers.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/os-level-virtualization] Whole-system virtualizers, however, can work with non-native file systems and create and roll back snapshots of the entire system state.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/stateless-protocol] A **stateless protocol** is a communication protocol in which the receiver does not retain session state from previous requests.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/stateless-protocol] The sender transfers relevant session state to the receiver in such a way that every request can be understood in isolation, without reference to session state from previous requests.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/stateless-protocol] In contrast, a **stateful protocol** is a communication protocol in which the receiver may retain session state from previous requests.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/stateless-protocol] In computer networks, examples of stateless protocols include the Internet Protocol (IP), which is the foundation for the Internet, and the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP), which is the foundation of the World Wide Web.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/stateless-protocol] Examples of stateful protocols include the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) and the File Transfer Protocol (FTP).
[src:gcp-cloud-run/stateless-protocol] Stateless protocols have superior visibility, reliability, and scalability properties.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/stateless-protocol] Visibility is improved because a monitoring system does not have to look beyond a single request in order to determine its full nature.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/stateless-protocol] Reliability is improved because it eases the task of recovering from failures such as packet loss.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/stateless-protocol] Scalability is improved because not having to store session state between requests allows the server to quickly free resources and further simplifies implementation.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/stateless-protocol] The disadvantage of stateless protocols is that they may decrease network performance by increasing the repetitive data sent in a series of requests, since that data is not retained or reused at the receiver.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/stateless-protocol] An HTTP server can understand each request in isolation.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/stateless-protocol] Contrast this with a traditional FTP server that conducts an interactive session with the user.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/stateless-protocol] During the session, a user is provided a means to be authenticated and set various variables (working directory, transfer mode), all stored on the server as part of the session state.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/stateless-protocol] There can be complex interactions between stateful and stateless protocols among different protocol layers.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/stateless-protocol] For example, HTTP, a stateless protocol, is layered on top of TCP, a stateful protocol, which is layered on top of IP, another stateless protocol, which is routed on a network that employs BGP, another stateful protocol, to direct the IP packets riding on the network.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/stateless-protocol] This stacking of layers continues even above HTTP.
[src:gcp-cloud-run/stateless-protocol] As a workaround for the lack of a retained session state, HTTP servers implement various session management methods, typically utilizing a session identifier in an HTTP cookie referencing a session state stored on the server, effectively creating a stateful protocol on top of HTTP.
